notes: Having the ORS on the riverbed, I expected all the oysters to do be dead. They were not. In fact, I don't think there was any change in the number of dead oysters. This may not be a useful conclusion as the oyster have been on the riverbed for only a month and these are not young oysters. While  people think of the month of October as a cold one, the water temperature was 65F and it was low tide which means water from upriver where its colder.  Therefore, average water temperature would be higher.  There were very few isopods relative to past visits but quite a few glass shrimp.

notes: This was the first measurement since the baseline last fall.  This was also a test of having the ORS on the river floor where most of the oyster eating critters live.  It was a test for mortality.  I did not consider it a good test as a larger number of oysters would likely do much better.  The water here is not very saline so some oyster killers are not found here at all which are common in more saline water eg. oyster drills.  Also, because this water is not so saline and is far from the mouth of the Hudson, there is considerable ice buildup during the winter.  Oysters and mussels overwintering cannot be floating near the surface as the top 6 inches of surface will be frozen or covered with sheets of ice.

I entered all the baseline data.  It would not save and a message kept appearing that said "Baseline data cannot be saved" even though all fields were completed.

Additionally, it did not determine the minimum and maximum size of oysters and there was nowhere to input that data.  It appeared as blank.  

Although I entered the measurement for each oyster on each tagged substrate, the individual measurements did not show up when I published my data.

notes:
Very odd cage setups reported to Robert Buchanan.

#18 the oysters in the bag and the 3 tagged oysters outside the bag were inaccessible unless I chose to open the end caps with a pair of pliers.  I did not write down that the oysters in the bag were tagged so perhaps they were not.  There was no mobile trap either.

The bottom section with the holes making it accessible had recruitment oysters.

#20  Registered to Megan Ashley and Erica  Azzareto.  I forget the specifics here.  I remember Megan's/Erica's cage being destroyed by the ice and possibly the bag in Scott's cage were their replacement oysters?

#21 Registered to Hana Kahn. All the oysters in the trap were dead.  That is the shells were open, nothing inside.  I assume the frigid temps killed them.  They were in an accessible part of the cage.  Also the mobile trap was wound around the shells, making them very difficult to remove.  The caps on the end of the top portion of the ORS were hanging loosely.  The dead oysters can serve as recruitment shells.

Scott's cage.  bag of untagged oysters, no mobile trap.  just one section. has sediment trap , no recruitment oysters.

#16 My cage.  It lost a few oysters overwinter but generally most are fine.  That cage was near or on the bottom at all times.

The bungee cord seems effective in holding the the two ORS sections together in case the knots are not tied tightly enough.

Bottom line.  Probably need 4 new cages and 4 sets of new tagged oysters and for overwintering the oysters should be tied near where mine are so they sit at or near the bottom.  The water here is not very saline (last week it was 8ppm, today just 13) so ice is real problem.  Maybe we should mix it up with some ribbed and blue mussels to see how they do?  I was at Soundview Park in March and was astounded by all the live wild ribbed mussels there. Tough buggers.  Also some live wild oysters but that's more saline and maybe ice is not such a problem.
